# BookmarkManager — Project Overview

LAN-only bookmark manager for ONE administrator, ONE desktop Brave profile, ONE extension install, ONE API container, ONE SQLite database. Do NOT add multi-user support, public hosting, Postgres, mobile clients, auto-scraping, or other-browser support without an explicit scope change (and doc update).

## Components

- `BookmarkExtension/` — Manifest V3 TypeScript extension. `src/background/service-worker.ts` runs the websocket loop, alarms, heartbeats, hotkeys, omnibox search. `src/bookmarks/bookmark-adapter.ts` translates server commands into `chrome.bookmarks` calls. **Only the extension may call `chrome.bookmarks`.**
- `src/BookmarkManager.Api/` — ASP.NET Core server, **sole writer of SQLite** (only one instance ever runs). Controllers and services split into partial classes by concern.
- `src/BookmarkManager.Client/` — Blazor **WebAssembly** + MudBlazor dashboard, served by the API under one origin.
- `src/BookmarkManager.Contracts/` — shared request/response DTOs between client and API. All cross-boundary DTOs live here — never duplicate types in Client and Api.

EF Core entities/migrations stay server-side — never referenced from the client.

## Sync model (1:1 state projection)

Extension polls `POST api/extension/heartbeat`; uploads full snapshot to `POST api/extension/snapshot` when tracked-root config changes; server enqueues moves/deletes/creates as `ExtensionCommandEntry` rows; extension claims leases via `POST api/extension/commands/claim`, executes with `chrome.bookmarks`, reports back via `POST api/extension/commands/{opId}/complete` with browser-side ID mappings. Server pushes to client + extension over raw WebSocket (`SyncWebSocketManager`, `api/sync/ws`) — **no SignalR anywhere, don't introduce it**.

Manager-only metadata (category/status/progress/tags/rating/notes/favorite/cover-image) is NEVER pushed to Brave. Soft-delete for 30 days with JSON backup before purge/repair/restore.

## Core invariants (breaking these causes sync storms or data loss)

- Update the desired bookmark projection and enqueue its command in the SAME database transaction.
- Preserve stable operation/event IDs, command leases, idempotent acknowledgements.
- **Never turn a Brave-originated event into a command back to Brave.**
- Folder-creation-then-move sequences must defer the move in the DB until the browser confirms the folder's `BrowserNodeId`.
- Add an EF Core migration for every model change; never rewrite an applied migration.
- Bookmark URLs restricted to absolute `http`/`https`.
- Persist correctness-critical extension state in the API or `chrome.storage.local`, never only in service-worker memory.
- Initial selected-root snapshot and explicit repair resync = Brave wins.

## Scope-change features (allowed, bounded)

- **Library** (`Docs/library-phases.md`): outbound read-only HTTP to public catalog APIs (AniList, MangaDex, Kitsu, RanobeDB, RoyalRoad, Novelfire) for discovery/browse only. Providers behind `IMediaProvider` in `src/BookmarkManager.Api/Services/Library/`. Novelfire is bulk-catalog-only — robots.txt disallows its search/API endpoints; never add live search against them. Library never writes to the bookmark tree.
- **In-Tab Command Palette**: extension `toggle-palette` command injects a `palette-host.html` iframe (via `activeTab` + `chrome.scripting`) framing the Blazor `/palette` page over https. Read-only page UI: never touches host page DOM beyond its own iframe, never writes bookmarks; palette origin comes from extension storage, never page-supplied params; cross-frame postMessage is origin-checked; relayed URLs restricted to `http`/`https`.

## Extension purpose

`BookmarkExtension/` exists purely for chaptered/episodic content — manga, manhwa, manhua, webnovels, light novels, anime. Bookmark URLs are chapter/episode pages of a series; duplicate detection is series-level via `seriesKeyFromUrl` in `src/bookmarks/duplicate-detector.ts` (chapter 124 and 125 of the same series ARE duplicates). Do not generalize extension UX toward generic bookmarking.

## Commands

.NET (.NET 10):
```powershell
dotnet restore BookmarkManager.sln
dotnet build BookmarkManager.sln --no-restore
dotnet test BookmarkManager.sln --no-build
```

**Do not run the full solution test suite while developing a feature** (~3 min; CI runs it on PR). Scope to the touched project or `dotnet test --filter "FullyQualifiedName~Name"`.

Extension:
```powershell
cd BookmarkExtension
npm ci
npm run typecheck
npm run lint
npm test          # vitest
npm run build     # esbuild via build.mjs
```

